# ============================================================================
# 16. PERFORMANCE RULES
# ============================================================================

- Use next/dynamic for below-fold components with loading skeletons
- Use Next.js Image component (NOT <img>) for all images
- Optimize imports: lucide-react is in optimizePackageImports
- Lazy-initialize external clients (Stripe, Resend) — never at module scope
- DB queries: use parallel Promise.all() where queries are independent
- Never import the entire lib/protocol-templates.ts — import specific functions
- Cache membership tier in JWT payload where possible (avoid per-request Stripe calls)

# ============================================================================
# 17. SECURITY RULES
# ============================================================================

- Validate ALL user input with Zod schemas before any DB/service call
- Sanitize rendered markdown with DOMPurify (lib/blog-content.ts, lib/library-content.ts)
- Webhook signature verification: ALWAYS verify before processing (Stripe, Cal.com, Daily.co)
- Rate limit sensitive endpoints (magic link, OTP, intake, club signup)
- HMAC tokens for admin approval links (30-min expiry)
- Presigned URLs for file uploads (never accept direct uploads)
- CORS: rely on Next.js defaults (same-origin)
- Never expose internal error details or stack traces to clients
- Authorize.net webhook: MUST reject when signature key is not configured

# ============================================================================
# 18. COMMON MISTAKES — GUARDRAILS
# ============================================================================

## DO NOT:
- Use 'use server' directive (this project uses API routes, not Server Actions)
- Create new Context providers without strong justification
- Add new npm dependencies without checking if existing tools cover the need
- Use default exports for non-UI-component modules (use named exports)
- Put business logic in components (extract to lib/)
- Call database functions from client components (go through API routes)
- Use inline styles (use Tailwind classes)
- Create helpers/abstractions for one-time operations
- Add features beyond what was asked
- Add docstrings/comments to code you didn't change
- Use stone/gray/slate colors (use brand tokens)
- Reference components/sections/* (dead code)
- Use raw fetch to Stripe/Asher Med/SiPhox (use lib/ wrappers)
- Trust raw `cultr_club_visitor` browser JSON for club member hydration or persist full club profiles in client-readable cookies/localStorage
- Hard-delete affiliate/company coupon codes that already have historical usage or `order_attributions` references
- Reuse built-in `CLUB_COUPONS` values for admin-created affiliate/company codes on `join.cultrhealth.com`

## DO:
- Read files before modifying them
- Follow existing patterns in the nearest similar file
- Use the cn() utility for all conditional class merging
- Coerce all NUMERIC DB columns with Number() or parseFloat()
- Use make_interval() for all SQL interval calculations
- Test changes with npx vitest run before committing
- Run npx tsc --noEmit to verify type safety
- Keep API routes thin — validate, call lib, respond
- Use existing shared components (MarketingHero, TrustStrip, SocialProofBadge, etc.)
- Check CLAUDE.md and CHANGELOG.md for recent changes before making assumptions
- Keep `cultr_club_visitor` as a signed minimal session token and rehydrate full club member data from the server only after token verification
- Hard-delete coupon codes only when they are unused and unreferenced; otherwise deactivate them to preserve creator ROI and attribution history
- Reject normalized collisions between admin-created coupon codes and built-in `CLUB_COUPONS` values

